      "references": "[ErGr80] Erd\\H{o}s, P. and Graham, R., Old and new problems and results in combinatorial number theory. Monographies de L'Enseignement Mathematique (1980).",
      "remarks": "Erd\\H{o}s and Graham \\cite{ErGr80} remark that very little is known about $T(A)$ in general. It is known that\\[T(n)=1, T(n^2)=128, T(n^3)=12758,\\]\\[T(n^4)=5134240,\\textrm{ and }T(n^5)=67898771.\\]Erd\\H{o}s and Graham remark that a good candidate for the $n$ in the question are $k=2^t$ for large $t$, perhaps even $t=3$, because of the highly restricted values of $n^{2^t}$ modulo $2^{t+1}$."
    },
